<subSubSection id="668165721A5F347394D90591FDD2A195" pageId="11" pageNumber="322" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="2E2436F91A5F347394D90591FDD2A195" blockId="11.[151,1437,1155,1902]" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">
<emphasis id="1CEFEAEB1A5F347394D90591FEE2A1EE" bold="true" box="[151,286,1156,1182]" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new genus is named after our colleague Jan Bosselaers (Royal Museum for Central Africa, Tervuren, 
<collectingCountry id="568C76691A5F347394A805B2FEB7A1B2" box="[230,331,1191,1218]" name="Belgium" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">Belgium</collectingCountry>
), in recognition of his contributions to arachnology, particularly to the systematics of 
<taxonomicName id="E99B4D7A1A5F3473915905B2FA61A1B1" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1897" box="[1303,1437,1191,1217]" class="Arachnida" family="Liocranidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="322" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Liocranidae</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="1CEFEAEB1A5F347394D905D9FEF4A196" box="[151,264,1228,1254]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">sensu lato</emphasis>
. The gender is masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="668165721A5F3473948905FAFD24A0CE" pageId="11" pageNumber="322" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="2E2436F91A5F3473948905FAFD24A0CE" blockId="11.[151,1437,1155,1902]" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">
<emphasis id="1CEFEAEB1A5F3473948905FAFEBEA07A" bold="true" box="[199,322,1263,1290]" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new genus differs from other 
<taxonomicName id="E99B4D7A1A5F347396F105FAFCA3A079" authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1892" box="[703,863,1263,1289]" class="Arachnida" family="Phrurolithidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="322" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Phrurolithidae</taxonomicName>
by lacking retrolateral tibial apophyses, the poorlydeveloped palpal femoral extension (
<emphasis id="1CEFEAEB1A5F3473960C0401FD9CA05D" box="[578,608,1300,1325]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">Fe</emphasis>
), and the lack of terminal and subterminal apophyses of the bulb (
<figureCitation id="B6A02A7C1A5F347391240406FF4EA022" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1840,1865]" captionTargetBox="[151,1432,597,1815]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1435,596,1815]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 10. Male palp (A–E) and leg I (F) of Bosselaerius hyrcanicus sp. n. A prolateral; B dorsal; C ventroprolateral; D ventral; E–F retrolateral. Scale=0.2 mm.Abbreviations: Dp—dorsoprolateral apophysis, Em—embolus, Fe—femoral extension, Sd—sperm duct." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3734520" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3734520/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">Figs 10</figureCitation>
C–E, 11A–C) (
<emphasis id="1CEFEAEB1A5F3473952E042DFE8BA021" box="[352,375,1336,1361]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">vs</emphasis>
. palpal tibia with at least one retrolateral apophysis, well-developed femoral extension [
<figureCitation id="B6A02A7C1A5F347391270422FF59A006" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1877,1902]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,933,1847]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1435,921,1853]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Copulatory organs of Phrurolithus azarkinae sp. n. A–C male palp, prolateral, ventral and retrolateral; D epigyne intact, ventral; E macerated epigyne, dorsal; F dissected epigyne, ventral. Scale=0.2 mm. Abbreviations: Co—copulatory opening, Em—embolus, Fd—fertilization duct, Fe—femoral extension, Gr—receptacular gland, Pr—primary receptacle, Ra—retrolateral apophysis, Sd—sperm duct, Sr—secondary receptacle, Va—retroventral apophysis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3734502" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3734502/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">Figs 2</figureCitation>
A–C, 4A, E–F] and presence of apophyses on the tegulum). At least the female of the 
<typeStatus id="F120885B1A5F347390CC0449FB4EA006" box="[1154,1202,1372,1398]" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">type</typeStatus>
species has a dorsal abdominal scutum (
<emphasis id="1CEFEAEB1A5F347395340495FE64A0E9" box="[378,408,1408,1433]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">vs.</emphasis>
absent in females of other genera and in 
<taxonomicName id="E99B4D7A1A5F347397360495FB59A0EA" authority="Zamani &amp; Marusik, 2020" authorityName="Zamani &amp; Marusik" authorityYear="2020" box="[888,1189,1408,1434]" class="Arachnida" family="Phrurolithidae" genus="Bosselaerius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="322" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tajikistanicus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="1CEFEAEB1A5F347397360495FB59A0EA" box="[888,1189,1408,1434]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">Bosselaerius tajikistanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="1CEFEAEB1A5F347390E10495FB0CA0EA" bold="true" box="[1199,1264,1408,1434]" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="07DC57901A5F347390E10495FB0CA0EA" box="[1199,1264,1408,1434]" pageId="11" pageNumber="322" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
), and a pair of distinct epigynal hoods (
<emphasis id="1CEFEAEB1A5F347395E504B1FE36A0CD" box="[427,458,1444,1469]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">vs.</emphasis>
absent in other genera).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="668165721A5F3473948904D2FF1CA21E" pageId="11" pageNumber="322" type="description">
<paragraph id="2E2436F91A5F3473948904D2FE5CA359" blockId="11.[151,1437,1155,1902]" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">
<emphasis id="1CEFEAEB1A5F3473948904D2FEA5A092" bold="true" box="[199,345,1479,1506]" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">Description.</emphasis>
Small, body length 
<quantity id="E9639B1C1A5F3473960D04D2FD46A092" box="[579,698,1479,1506]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.75" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="322" unit="mm" value="2.75" valueMax="3.5" valueMin="2.0">2–3.5 mm</quantity>
. Each chelicera with strong frontal spine. Tibia I with 5 pairs of ventral spines in males and 7 pairs in females. Female of the 
<typeStatus id="F120885B1A5F3473970304F9FC81A376" box="[845,893,1516,1542]" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">type</typeStatus>
species with small dorsal scutum; absent or unknown in other species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E2436F91A5F347394890726FE3DA271" blockId="11.[151,1437,1155,1902]" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">
Male palp: femur with small ventral extension; tibia without retrolateral apophyses, but with only one small, almost indistinct, dorso-prolateral, spine-like apophysis; tibia distally with dense setae hiding apophysis; bulb lacking apophyses; sperm duct long, reaching middle part of the tegulum, not narrowed in the base of embolus (
<emphasis id="1CEFEAEB1A5F347391200769FA70A3E5" box="[1390,1420,1660,1685]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">Be</emphasis>
); base of embolus massive, embolus small, spine-like, directed antero-retrolaterally, embolus accompanied with teeth (
<emphasis id="1CEFEAEB1A5F347394EF07D1FF46A3AD" box="[161,186,1732,1757]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">Te</emphasis>
) subequal in size to embolus. Epigyne with a pair of distinct anterior hoods (
<emphasis id="1CEFEAEB1A5F3473906C07D1FBBDA3AE" box="[1058,1089,1732,1758]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">Ah</emphasis>
); secondary (membranous) receptacles small or lacking.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E2436F91A5F34739489061EFF1CA21E" blockId="11.[151,1437,1155,1902]" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">
<emphasis id="1CEFEAEB1A5F34739489061EFE9BA256" bold="true" box="[199,359,1803,1830]" pageId="11" pageNumber="322">Composition.</emphasis>
